WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.440
Alright, so thanks for coming this morning, or this afternoon, or wherever you're at.

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:20.959
So we're going to talk about a new R package called Recipes, and its purpose is mostly

00:00:20.959 --> 00:00:29.480
about creating design matrices and datasets and pre-processing them with various techniques

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:32.720
that we'll go into more.

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:39.119
So just to maybe get started, talk about a simple linear model that we might use.

00:00:39.119 --> 00:00:44.439
And there's a dataset in Carat, so if you were to load Carat and load the dataset Sacramento,

00:00:44.439 --> 00:00:51.560
what you'd find is a dataset where there are data for houses that were sold in Sacramento

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:53.439
within a five-day period.

00:00:53.439 --> 00:00:57.160
So there are things like the sale price of the house, the square footage, number of beds

00:00:57.160 --> 00:01:00.759
and baths, there's like longitude and latitude and that kind of thing.

00:01:00.759 --> 00:01:05.000
There's also the type of house, which oddly only has three levels.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.959
But that's all in that dataset, and let's assume that you wanted to build a model to

00:01:08.959 --> 00:01:11.400
predict the price of a house.

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:17.199
So you might think about using LM to do that, and to create this model, you use the LM function,

00:01:17.199 --> 00:01:18.800
and LM takes a formula.

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:23.680
And so we'll be talking about formulas a little bit, and you know, just as a demonstration

00:01:23.680 --> 00:01:27.639
formula, this is not probably how I would model these data, but you might take the log

00:01:27.639 --> 00:01:31.400
of the price because it's a very skewed variable, and that's your outcomes, and so it's on the

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:33.480
left-hand side of the tilde there.

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:37.360
And then on the right-hand side, we have basically a symbolic representation of what our model

00:01:37.360 --> 00:01:38.360
is going to be.

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:43.800
And basically this says, you know, we're going to model log of price as a function of the

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:49.519
type of house and its square footage, and that data is in this data frame called Sacramento.

00:01:49.519 --> 00:01:54.919
And then with LM and formula methods, you can add a little bit here that's a subset

00:01:54.919 --> 00:01:55.919
command.

00:01:55.919 --> 00:02:00.360
So this would filter the Sacramento data to look only for where there are three or more

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:05.199
bedrooms, if that's the data you want to nail on.

00:02:05.199 --> 00:02:10.039
And so basically the purpose of the code chunk, if you take it step-by-step, is, you know,

00:02:10.039 --> 00:02:14.240
the first thing it would do would be to subset the dataset that you're going to model using

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:15.880
that command.

00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:19.679
And then it creates what's called a design matrix, which is, if you think about linear

00:02:19.679 --> 00:02:24.559
regression, we usually think of, like, you know, Y is equal to X beta plus epsilon, and

00:02:24.559 --> 00:02:28.839
the X part of that is the predictors, and that's what the old-school people like me

00:02:28.839 --> 00:02:31.399
would call a design matrix.

00:02:31.399 --> 00:02:35.520
So the second thing that that function does is to create a design matrix.

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:36.520
Now there's two predictors.

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:41.000
There's type and square footage, but you end up getting three model terms.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:45.039
The type variable is a factor, and that factor has three levels.

00:02:45.199 --> 00:02:50.440
And so when it creates dummy variables for that, it will actually make two columns of

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:55.320
that three-level factor that are zero and one for the different types of houses, and

00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:57.039
then you have the third term for square footage.

00:02:57.039 --> 00:03:02.600
So your design matrix, even though you have two predictors, actually has the non-intercept

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:07.399
parts of that design matrix are those three columns.

00:03:07.399 --> 00:03:10.479
And then the third thing it does would be to log transform the outcome variable, which

00:03:10.479 --> 00:03:13.759
is price, and then it actually gets around to actually fitting the linear regression

00:03:13.759 --> 00:03:18.559
model using LM.fit and some other stuff that we don't normally mess with.

00:03:18.559 --> 00:03:23.440
But anyway, the first two steps that is really the part that it creates a design matrix.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:30.240
And again, we usually, not going to be formulas really in here, but we represent that as X.

00:03:30.240 --> 00:03:35.919
So I wrote for RStudio a couple of blog posts on the formula method.

00:03:35.919 --> 00:03:40.399
And so just summarizing, and I have a link to those in the slides, and you can find those.

00:03:40.399 --> 00:03:44.759
But basically, the great thing about the model form is it's very expressive.

00:03:44.759 --> 00:03:49.600
So you can say what your predictor is, what your outcome is.

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:54.639
You can have these inline functions, like logging price will ensure that that happens

00:03:54.639 --> 00:03:55.639
in the...

00:03:55.639 --> 00:03:57.660
You don't have to pre-log your data.

00:03:57.660 --> 00:04:01.600
You can have interaction terms and nesting and all sorts of great things, so they're

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:02.600
very expressive.

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:07.360
And if you're doing something that's pretty simple, like the housing model I was showing,

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:12.080
it's extremely efficient and nice to use.

00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:15.199
Under the hood, and this is what the blog post goes into, it actually does some pretty

00:04:15.199 --> 00:04:19.799
elegant functional programming, which surprises me that that's been...

00:04:19.799 --> 00:04:24.399
I've been looking at it for years, but that's been around for quite a long time in the original

00:04:24.399 --> 00:04:25.660
S language.

00:04:25.660 --> 00:04:30.600
So you don't really think of R as a functional programming language, but a core part of that,

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:36.359
the model.matrix and LM and all that is pretty nicely done functionally.

00:04:36.359 --> 00:04:40.880
And again, I kind of already mentioned this, you can embed functions in the formula like

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:45.920
I did with price here, and the cool thing about that is if we were to log, let's say,

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:51.079
square footage, not only can we do that inline, and it would log that variable for the data

00:04:51.079 --> 00:04:55.239
that you have that you're feeding the model on, when you go to use the predict function

00:04:55.239 --> 00:04:58.440
on a new data set, again, you don't have to pre-log square footage.

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:03.160
You would just give it the column of square footage, and since it knows it's recorded

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:06.880
that transformation in the formula, it can actually apply to that, to whatever you're

00:05:06.880 --> 00:05:08.959
interested in.

00:05:08.959 --> 00:05:16.640
There's some limitations to what the function or the formula framework can do, and as I'll

00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:21.720
talk about in the next few slides, there's some inefficiencies that can occur there.

00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:25.720
It's mostly, I think, because it's a really amazingly well-designed system, but it was

00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:32.040
designed where I think nobody envisioned having maybe hundreds of variables in their model,

00:05:32.040 --> 00:05:36.839
and the sort of large-scale modeling that people can do today, and so I think it sort

00:05:36.839 --> 00:05:39.519
of suffers a little bit in those instances.

00:05:39.519 --> 00:05:43.200
So just some examples of that is let's say you want to do something a little more complicated

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:44.200
with your features.

00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:50.119
Let's say you have some missing data that you need to impute, and then you're putting

00:05:50.119 --> 00:05:53.640
that data into a model like a support vector machine or partial least squares or something

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:58.799
where you need to center and scale those values, and so you can envision maybe doing something

00:05:58.799 --> 00:06:02.480
with formula where you have an outcome, an utility, and then since you have these inline

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:07.119
functions, you might think that, well, I want to impute my variable first based on k-nearest

00:06:07.119 --> 00:06:11.679
neighbors, and then since I need to center and scale, I can center them and take the

00:06:11.679 --> 00:06:16.519
output of that and scale it, and that seems fine, but that's problematic on a lot of levels

00:06:16.519 --> 00:06:21.000
in terms of how the formula infrastructure works, and one of those being that if you

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.600
need to impute a bunch of variables, let's say with k-nearest neighbors, you would need

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:31.720
to store the original data set, and since the functional programming bit of LM deals

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:36.640
with each variable separately, you'd end up storing the same data set many, many times

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:39.040
for every variable you want to impute.

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:43.079
So not only is it problematic just from a programming standpoint, just even if this

00:06:43.079 --> 00:06:48.480
code would work, it's kind of a bad idea because you end up having many, many variations or

00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:50.519
the same data set included many times.

00:06:50.519 --> 00:06:57.320
So this is not a terribly obscure thing to do, but it does limit you to what you can

00:06:57.320 --> 00:06:59.000
do in the formula method.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:05.559
Another thing is there are a lot of modeling functions such as LM and Rparts, a good example,

00:07:05.559 --> 00:07:09.160
where you don't have a non-format interface to the model, so you're constrained to always

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:13.119
specify your model using a formula, and the problem with that is you can't really recycle

00:07:13.119 --> 00:07:14.119
things.

00:07:14.119 --> 00:07:18.119
So if you've already done all the work to generate the design matrix for LM, there's

00:07:18.200 --> 00:07:21.920
no way to take that and recycle it into Rpart.

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:25.440
So that's problematic in a way.

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:29.000
Another thing that I won't get into too much, but you can find it in the blog post that's

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:37.640
linked down here, is that the way the formula method information is stored is pretty inefficient,

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:40.480
and it's especially inefficient when you have a large number of variables.

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:46.839
So we show in that blog post, based on using Rpart or Random Forest, that if you have a

00:07:46.839 --> 00:07:51.600
lot of predictors, like in the thousands, you can spend maybe half the time of that

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:54.519
modeling function just creating the design matrix.

00:07:54.519 --> 00:07:57.820
So it does have some weaknesses for particularly wide datasets.

00:07:57.820 --> 00:08:02.160
It's not really weak in the sense of if I had millions of data points, like rows, but

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:08.040
when you think about columns, the way it stores the information about the formula is not efficient,

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:13.160
and I wouldn't say it exponentially increases in inefficiency as the number of predictors

00:08:13.279 --> 00:08:17.200
goes up, but it's not good.

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:18.940
So that's not great.

00:08:18.940 --> 00:08:23.640
Another thing that isn't necessarily a limitation, but it's always sort of confounded me, is

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:27.679
if you're going to do anything multivariately, you want to specify more than one thing on

00:08:27.679 --> 00:08:31.839
the left-hand side of the formula, and you would need to wrap those in Cbind, which is

00:08:31.839 --> 00:08:35.039
just kind of ugly.

00:08:35.039 --> 00:08:38.280
So that's something that we don't like.

00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:42.280
And then another more fundamental aspect of formulas is there's really a limited set of

00:08:42.400 --> 00:08:44.440
roles that variables in your dataset can take.

00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:49.960
And again, as we do things that are more complicated beyond linear regression, that becomes a big

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:55.520
sort of more philosophical limiting factor of what this formula technology can do.

00:08:55.520 --> 00:08:59.179
So as an example of that, let's say you're fitting like a hierarchical model, whether

00:08:59.179 --> 00:09:06.359
it's using Stan or LME or whatnot, you have variables in your dataset that are going to

00:09:06.359 --> 00:09:12.559
be included as outcomes and predictors, but then you have data that define the hierarchy.

00:09:12.559 --> 00:09:18.440
So if you take this example from the LME4 documentation, you have a subject effect.

00:09:18.440 --> 00:09:24.359
So you're modeling in the sleep study, you're modeling this outcome called a reaction as

00:09:24.359 --> 00:09:26.039
a function of days.

00:09:26.039 --> 00:09:31.080
And I think this model is a random coefficient model that would give you a hard to model

00:09:31.080 --> 00:09:35.500
based on with random effects, probably for the intercept in days.

00:09:35.500 --> 00:09:39.820
And those intercept, those random effects are connected to the subject specification.

00:09:39.820 --> 00:09:45.140
And so subject is not a predictor, but it's something you need to carry along with a role

00:09:45.140 --> 00:09:50.500
is your ID variable for the methodology.

00:09:50.500 --> 00:09:55.219
And so that's the reason that this formula looks different than the others is because

00:09:55.219 --> 00:09:59.140
that particular package in a way had to sort of rewrite the formula method to make that

00:09:59.140 --> 00:10:02.700
work because that's what they needed.

00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:06.820
Another example is something called the Bradley-Terry 2 package, and that's kind of an interesting

00:10:06.820 --> 00:10:10.900
package that can model competitions between variables.

00:10:10.900 --> 00:10:17.900
So like if you had a boxing, data on boxing, you might be modeling whether one person can

00:10:17.900 --> 00:10:20.460
win over another and you might have a dozen people.

00:10:20.460 --> 00:10:25.380
And so the thing is, you might want to model that as a function of let's say reach.

00:10:25.380 --> 00:10:31.500
And so in the Bradley-Terry model, it's basically like a souped up logistic regression, but

00:10:31.500 --> 00:10:36.340
in order to have that formula method work in this instance, they sort of had to invent

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:40.859
a new way of doing formulas simply because the current methodology doesn't let you really

00:10:40.859 --> 00:10:42.700
specify things.

00:10:42.700 --> 00:10:49.700
And then another example is there's a boosting method called mob, and you can imagine it's

00:10:49.700 --> 00:10:55.780
sort of like a recursive partitioning model like our part, but it fits linear models in

00:10:55.780 --> 00:10:56.780
the terminal nodes.

00:10:56.780 --> 00:11:00.900
And so when you fit this model, you want to specify which variables are used for splitting

00:11:00.900 --> 00:11:05.700
to make the tree, and then which variables are used in the model in the terminal nodes.

00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:10.299
And so they wrote a whole new package called model tools that will allow you to have sort

00:11:10.299 --> 00:11:11.859
of multiple formulas.

00:11:11.859 --> 00:11:16.640
And so again, with the bar here, this is another situation where people needed different roles

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:17.640
of these predictors.

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:19.900
You have predictors that you want to use for splitting and predictors that you want to

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:26.179
use for modeling, and that sort of is not really going to happen in the current standard

00:11:26.179 --> 00:11:27.500
formula method.

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:31.179
So if you think about maybe other roles, the ones I could think of, if you have the traditional

00:11:31.179 --> 00:11:35.659
predictors and outcomes, sometimes you have stratification variables, like if you're doing

00:11:35.659 --> 00:11:40.940
a clinical trial and you want to stratify over sites, that's a separate variable again

00:11:40.940 --> 00:11:46.260
that's not, you're not necessarily doing direct computations on it, but you need it.

00:11:46.260 --> 00:11:49.700
A lot of models, when we want to capture the performance of the model, sometimes that involves

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:50.940
other data.

00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:54.380
So if we're predicting whether someone's going to repay a loan or not, we don't necessarily

00:11:54.380 --> 00:11:55.700
care about the accuracy of that model.

00:11:55.700 --> 00:11:59.260
We care about the expected loss that comes from that, and if you're going to compute

00:11:59.260 --> 00:12:03.340
the expected profit, you're going to need something like the loan amount.

00:12:03.340 --> 00:12:06.500
So again, it's another variable that you need to carry along, but it's not really a predictor

00:12:06.500 --> 00:12:07.500
or an outcome.

00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:10.380
So you can't really do much with the standard formula for that.

00:12:10.380 --> 00:12:15.619
There's a variety of other things like fastening or random effects, like I mentioned.

00:12:15.619 --> 00:12:21.260
Now case weights and offsets are kind of special cases and sometimes error terms, because there

00:12:21.260 --> 00:12:25.219
have been some exceptions written to the formula method where you could have like an offset

00:12:25.219 --> 00:12:27.940
variable and declare that in the formula method.

00:12:27.940 --> 00:12:32.340
Those are kind of hard-coded things that are in the base package, and they're not easily

00:12:32.340 --> 00:12:34.059
extensible to have one for stratification.

00:12:34.059 --> 00:12:38.979
Well, there is a strata function in the survival package, but you can just by point is if you

00:12:38.979 --> 00:12:42.020
had an arbitrary rule that you're creating, you can't really do that with the current

00:12:42.020 --> 00:12:43.580
set of formulas.

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:47.260
So to me, philosophically, this is the larger problem.

00:12:47.260 --> 00:12:52.299
You know, all the programming aspects of formulas that we don't like so much, like the inefficiency

00:12:52.299 --> 00:12:55.539
sometimes can be programmed out, but this is something I think is really baked into

00:12:55.539 --> 00:12:56.539
the system.

00:12:56.539 --> 00:13:01.900
So we came up with this idea of something called a recipe, and there's a big food analogy

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:03.380
that's going to happen here.

00:13:03.380 --> 00:13:07.260
And so basically the idea of a recipe is you can think of a recipe really as a sequence

00:13:07.260 --> 00:13:08.260
of steps, right?

00:13:08.260 --> 00:13:11.659
So you're going to make a lasagna, it tells you what the ingredients are, and it says,

00:13:11.659 --> 00:13:14.059
you know, assemble it like this and then bake the thing.

00:13:14.059 --> 00:13:18.580
But if you think about the linear model we had earlier, you know, a sequence of steps

00:13:18.580 --> 00:13:21.460
might be saying, hey, you know, prices are outcome.

00:13:21.460 --> 00:13:23.419
That's maybe step one to declare that.

00:13:23.419 --> 00:13:27.059
And then we might declare the predictors to be type and square foot.

00:13:27.059 --> 00:13:31.260
And then another thing we did there in LM was to say, well, we should log transform

00:13:31.260 --> 00:13:32.260
price.

00:13:32.260 --> 00:13:36.780
And then the fourth thing we did, we could say that that sequence of steps is, you know,

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:39.859
let's convert that type variable into dummy variables.

00:13:39.859 --> 00:13:46.539
And that kind of defines the procedure that the LM formula method, you know, the formula

00:13:46.539 --> 00:13:50.419
method with LM actually did when we first showed that code.

00:13:50.419 --> 00:13:54.780
And so the thing is a recipe, at least as I've stated here, is really what we're intending

00:13:54.780 --> 00:13:55.780
to do.

00:13:55.780 --> 00:13:56.780
It's not actually doing it necessarily.

00:13:56.780 --> 00:14:01.179
So one of the issues with, you know, model.matrix and all that is the specification of what

00:14:01.179 --> 00:14:04.340
you want to do is coupled directly with doing it.

00:14:04.340 --> 00:14:10.979
So that's one of the reasons you can't really recycle things very easily between methodologies.

00:14:10.979 --> 00:14:14.539
So you know, what recipes does is basically says, well, let's specify what we want to

00:14:14.539 --> 00:14:15.539
do.

00:14:15.539 --> 00:14:19.299
And then we won't actually, we'll delay the execution of that doing until we, you know,

00:14:19.419 --> 00:14:22.700
say, well, these are the data we want to do it with.

00:14:22.700 --> 00:14:28.659
So we kind of separate the planning of what we want to do from actually making it happen.

00:14:28.659 --> 00:14:32.780
I'll show you there's a link in the slides.

00:14:32.780 --> 00:14:35.299
But if you want to install it, it's not a crane yet.

00:14:35.299 --> 00:14:39.380
But there's a GitHub page for it here.

00:14:39.380 --> 00:14:41.179
And it's got, you know, a lot of examples.

00:14:41.179 --> 00:14:46.460
And as you can imagine, you've seen my other packages, there's a boatload of documentation.

00:14:46.460 --> 00:14:50.539
So right now, if you want to use it, you basically load the or install or load the

00:14:50.539 --> 00:14:56.580
DevTools package, and then use install into our GitHub with my GitHub ID and recipes.

00:14:56.580 --> 00:15:01.859
And that's currently the way you get it, but it really should be on CRAN pretty soon.

00:15:01.859 --> 00:15:06.820
So this will be linked in the slides.

00:15:06.820 --> 00:15:10.219
So once you load that, just for convenience, I also load a dplyr so we can get the pipe

00:15:10.219 --> 00:15:12.780
operator and some other things.

00:15:12.780 --> 00:15:17.219
And so if we wanted to reproduce maybe what Ellen was doing before, we start off, I'll

00:15:17.219 --> 00:15:19.820
show you a different way to create the initial recipe.

00:15:19.820 --> 00:15:23.739
But if we only have prediction outcomes, if you don't have any special roles that we want

00:15:23.739 --> 00:15:29.219
to apply to our data, we can start with basically a symbolic representation of what should be

00:15:29.219 --> 00:15:33.979
in the model by saying price is, you know, a function of type and square footage.

00:15:33.979 --> 00:15:37.820
Now, the data that you use here doesn't have to be the original data.

00:15:37.820 --> 00:15:43.260
It's just what we do in this particular step is we want to record what data are in that

00:15:43.260 --> 00:15:48.359
data frame and what their their attributes are, like are they factors or the numbers

00:15:48.359 --> 00:15:49.359
and so on.

00:15:49.359 --> 00:15:53.539
So this doesn't have to be a large data set if you have a very large data set, which of

00:15:53.539 --> 00:15:57.739
the recipe basically you don't have to use pipes, but I'll do that for convenience here

00:15:57.739 --> 00:16:00.340
is you can start adding steps to the recipe.

00:16:00.340 --> 00:16:05.700
So if we want to take the original recipe and add a step that says, hey, log transform

00:16:05.700 --> 00:16:11.340
this variable, we could do this little bit and that basically modifies the recipe to

00:16:11.340 --> 00:16:16.659
include a step of that recipe saying the log that variable called price.

00:16:16.659 --> 00:16:23.140
And then another thing we can do is to say to add on to that is to convert type to dummy

00:16:23.140 --> 00:16:24.140
variables.

00:16:24.140 --> 00:16:28.400
And so at that point, what we've done is we've come up with a specification of what the roles

00:16:28.400 --> 00:16:31.979
are using this for the method like we used before.

00:16:31.979 --> 00:16:36.739
And then we've talked about or described what kind of preprocessing or actions we want to

00:16:36.739 --> 00:16:42.380
happen for those variables by just adding these steps to it.

00:16:42.380 --> 00:16:46.659
And so it's fairly reminiscent if you've ever used care to the sort of in some ways, like

00:16:46.659 --> 00:16:52.299
the preprocess part of care where you can decide what kind of preprocessing you want

00:16:52.299 --> 00:16:53.299
with your variables.

00:16:53.299 --> 00:16:57.900
But again, all this does at this point is it says, well, what is the specification?

00:16:57.900 --> 00:16:58.900
What I want to do.

00:16:58.940 --> 00:17:03.940
And all we've said at this point was price of the outcome type and square footage or

00:17:03.940 --> 00:17:06.900
predictors, we're going to log price and create dummy variables for type.

00:17:06.900 --> 00:17:09.979
It doesn't actually do anything but record those actions.

00:17:09.979 --> 00:17:14.739
And then in this whole food analogy, we want to take this recipe and prepare it.

00:17:14.739 --> 00:17:19.699
Then what prepare does is basically you can think of it as training or learning or fitting

00:17:19.699 --> 00:17:21.859
the preprocessing steps.

00:17:21.859 --> 00:17:25.500
So, for example, we have dummy variables here for type.

00:17:25.540 --> 00:17:30.219
So when we do this, we're just saying we want to make dummy variables when we run prepare.

00:17:30.219 --> 00:17:34.180
What it actually does is interrogates the data that we've given it and says, OK, what

00:17:34.180 --> 00:17:37.619
are the levels of type and how exactly am I going to make those dummy variables?

00:17:37.939 --> 00:17:42.420
So once you start prepare, that's when you're actually doing computations and storing

00:17:42.420 --> 00:17:45.219
information about the specifics of those actions.

00:17:46.260 --> 00:17:49.619
Now, one little thing that I've done here you wouldn't necessarily have to do is I'm

00:17:49.619 --> 00:17:50.900
saying retain equal true.

00:17:51.140 --> 00:17:54.900
And what that says is take the data set that I've given it.

00:17:54.900 --> 00:18:00.619
And when you estimate these actions that you're going to do for the recipe, keep the

00:18:00.619 --> 00:18:04.819
modified version of that training set around, keep it in this object.

00:18:05.099 --> 00:18:09.219
And that'll stop us from having to redo computations over and over again.

00:18:09.380 --> 00:18:10.660
So that's a nice little feature.

00:18:10.780 --> 00:18:14.900
And you'll see that I'll mention that in a few minutes when I'm showing how things are

00:18:14.900 --> 00:18:16.180
sort of cached when we do this.

00:18:16.780 --> 00:18:19.260
So, again, we've specified what the actions are.

00:18:19.459 --> 00:18:22.339
We've sort of estimated things that we need to estimate.

00:18:22.660 --> 00:18:24.660
And then when you do that, it tells you which steps.

00:18:24.660 --> 00:18:25.660
There's a verbose option.

00:18:25.660 --> 00:18:28.739
But right now it tells you what steps are being executed as they're executed.

00:18:29.099 --> 00:18:33.099
And then when we actually want to get the design matrix to put an LM, the analogy here

00:18:33.099 --> 00:18:34.459
is we're going to bake that recipe.

00:18:34.739 --> 00:18:39.500
So we take the the object that we created that has all the information we need from the

00:18:39.500 --> 00:18:45.660
data. And then the new data option here says, well, you know, apply this this recipe to

00:18:45.660 --> 00:18:48.939
this data set. So if you're like in the machine learning or the

00:18:48.939 --> 00:18:51.339
predict modeling world, you might have a training, a test set.

00:18:52.020 --> 00:18:56.020
And so you can apply these operations that you estimate from your training set to the

00:18:56.020 --> 00:18:58.260
test set or to any new samples that you get.

00:18:58.900 --> 00:19:03.900
It's kind of like a predictor and apply method where you're basically projecting all

00:19:03.900 --> 00:19:07.020
the preprocessing methods on whatever data set you're interested in.

00:19:07.180 --> 00:19:08.739
And that will give you your design matrix.

00:19:11.540 --> 00:19:17.540
So so that's the basic idea behind recipes is you specify what you want, you estimate

00:19:17.540 --> 00:19:20.780
the things that you need to estimate, and then you apply it at will to whatever data

00:19:20.780 --> 00:19:23.459
sets that you want, which could be the original data set like it was here.

00:19:24.339 --> 00:19:25.459
And that's the basic idea.

00:19:25.459 --> 00:19:28.939
So the rest of it is sort of talking about the features and some of the things that you

00:19:28.939 --> 00:19:33.339
can do. Now, one of the things you may have noticed here is, you know, when I created

00:19:33.339 --> 00:19:36.339
this step for price, you know, I'm not quoting any variables here.

00:19:36.339 --> 00:19:40.859
And if you're a person who's used deep wire, you can see some similarity here where

00:19:40.859 --> 00:19:43.819
there's a bunch of deep wire like things happening here.

00:19:43.819 --> 00:19:47.500
Like we can pipe in information and sort of update objects.

00:19:47.500 --> 00:19:50.579
And you can see I'm not having to quote variables when I do this.

00:19:51.500 --> 00:19:56.500
But the interesting thing about recipes is unlike deep wire, we might want to specify

00:19:56.500 --> 00:19:59.660
what variables are using different steps based on more than their name.

00:19:59.780 --> 00:20:03.579
So right now, and as I'll show you in a minute, you can specify any number of variables

00:20:03.579 --> 00:20:08.180
in these steps by using their name or the standard deep wire things like matches or

00:20:08.180 --> 00:20:12.420
starts with. So you can use these sort of like functions to declare what variables are

00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:14.020
used in the steps.

00:20:14.339 --> 00:20:18.380
But sometimes we might want to do, let's say, dummy variables and do it on all the all

00:20:18.380 --> 00:20:22.619
the variables that I have in the data set that are not numeric, that let's say are

00:20:22.619 --> 00:20:27.420
factor variables. And so we also have these selectors that you can use that are things

00:20:27.420 --> 00:20:28.540
like all numeric.

00:20:29.060 --> 00:20:34.339
So if we want to have a step, we can say, well, do that for all the numeric predictors

00:20:34.339 --> 00:20:38.300
that are in my data set or do it on all the predictors or all the outcomes.

00:20:38.300 --> 00:20:41.099
And you can add and subtract these like you would with deep wire.

00:20:41.660 --> 00:20:46.060
So, for example, if you want to do PCA, you can't really do that on factor variables.

00:20:46.380 --> 00:20:52.300
So you might want to specify do it on all the predictors that are numeric and then you

00:20:52.300 --> 00:20:56.420
can do that like sort of like you have here the sequence of selectors.

00:20:56.579 --> 00:21:00.859
We can always just type the names and with common delimited unquoted variable names.

00:21:00.859 --> 00:21:07.140
But if you want to be a little more concise about what you're doing, you can do that.

00:21:07.420 --> 00:21:11.780
Now, one interesting aspect of a recipe is you might be doing or you might be saying

00:21:11.780 --> 00:21:16.180
let's do some operations on variables that don't necessarily exist yet.

00:21:16.859 --> 00:21:21.020
So, for example, if you're going to discretize predictors or, as you'll see in a little

00:21:21.020 --> 00:21:26.859
bit, do like PCA feature extraction, you might do PCA and say, give me the number of

00:21:26.859 --> 00:21:30.579
PCA variables that capture 95 percent of the variability.

00:21:31.060 --> 00:21:34.780
And that might be four of them or it might be a hundred of them, depending on the data

00:21:34.780 --> 00:21:36.380
set and the correlation structure and all that.

00:21:36.699 --> 00:21:41.020
So what's interesting about recipes is you might be making you might be wanting to do

00:21:41.020 --> 00:21:44.780
operations in the variables that actually don't not even exist yet, but you don't know

00:21:44.780 --> 00:21:45.859
how many of them there are.

00:21:46.420 --> 00:21:51.180
So, you know, you can do things like, you know, matches, you know, PC one through nine,

00:21:51.180 --> 00:21:54.699
which would capture, you know, the first whatever principal components you have there

00:21:54.939 --> 00:21:57.979
and then make sure that you also capture the numeric predictors.

00:21:57.979 --> 00:21:59.579
But maybe your outcome is numeric.

00:21:59.579 --> 00:22:00.900
You might want to get rid of that one.

00:22:01.300 --> 00:22:05.020
So you have a really, really rich set of way to specify variables in these recipes.

00:22:06.380 --> 00:22:11.339
And then we have a whole part of the vignette or the website has a whole vignette on

00:22:11.339 --> 00:22:14.420
selecting variables and examples of different ways of doing that.

00:22:15.339 --> 00:22:16.180
There's quite a lot there.

00:22:19.459 --> 00:22:24.060
All right, so one cool thing about the recipes is you can start with a recipe like the

00:22:24.060 --> 00:22:29.180
one we have, the current recipe we have all the only thing it does is really logs the

00:22:29.180 --> 00:22:30.939
outcome, increase dummy variables.

00:22:31.219 --> 00:22:34.459
But again, let's say you want to center and scale your data and then maybe apply.

00:22:34.739 --> 00:22:37.540
It wouldn't really make sense for this particular example, but let's say you want to

00:22:37.540 --> 00:22:39.459
apply PCA signal extraction.

00:22:39.939 --> 00:22:44.660
Well, once you have your your recipe, whether it's been trained or not, you can just

00:22:44.660 --> 00:22:48.540
keep adding steps to it and make that a different a different recipe.

00:22:48.540 --> 00:22:53.020
So you can sort of save in a way you can sort of like catch where you've gotten so far,

00:22:53.260 --> 00:22:56.260
save it as another name and add other steps to it.

00:22:56.260 --> 00:23:00.699
And I'll show an example of this towards the end with some dimension reduction routines.

00:23:01.180 --> 00:23:05.739
So if we start off this recipe that we've already done some computations on, we add

00:23:05.739 --> 00:23:11.380
some more steps when we go to prepare this recipe, it doesn't need to redo the ones

00:23:11.380 --> 00:23:12.699
that have already been executed.

00:23:13.140 --> 00:23:18.099
So you can you know, when we go to prepare the recipe with our training set, step

00:23:18.099 --> 00:23:22.739
center is going to need it to calculate all the means of the numeric predictors and step

00:23:22.739 --> 00:23:26.219
scale, calculate the standard deviations of all the numeric predictors.

00:23:26.699 --> 00:23:30.380
And then when it calculates the loadings and things like that for PCA, that's the things

00:23:30.380 --> 00:23:35.140
to prepare. We'll do it won't redo necessarily the things which the things that you've

00:23:35.140 --> 00:23:37.780
already done in the recipe.

00:23:38.140 --> 00:23:45.459
So when I go to run prepare on this new recipe now, I didn't say new data equal or I'm

00:23:45.459 --> 00:23:47.819
sorry, training data equal to Sacramento.

00:23:48.140 --> 00:23:51.060
And the reason I didn't have to do that is this retain equal true.

00:23:51.500 --> 00:23:57.060
If I don't if I don't retain the original predictors, the original data set, then I

00:23:57.060 --> 00:23:58.260
would need to add that here.

00:23:58.459 --> 00:24:04.500
But the value of having that sort of retain is when you go to do this new set of

00:24:04.500 --> 00:24:08.180
processing, you can see when it gives you the log of what it's doing.

00:24:08.180 --> 00:24:11.260
It puts pre-trained here because it's telling you I don't need to redo those

00:24:11.260 --> 00:24:16.020
computations because nothing's changed and that it does all the estimation needs to do

00:24:16.020 --> 00:24:17.020
for the remaining steps.

00:24:17.420 --> 00:24:22.060
So the cool thing about this is, let's say you want to try a bunch of different things.

00:24:22.420 --> 00:24:26.099
You created a bunch of different, let's say, design matrices to see what works for your

00:24:26.099 --> 00:24:27.260
model or your data.

00:24:27.660 --> 00:24:31.260
And let's say, again, you have some expensive imputation step that you need to do

00:24:31.699 --> 00:24:34.859
before you start doing these things because you have missing data where you can do that

00:24:34.859 --> 00:24:38.819
imputation step, which might be sort of computationally taxing, but you don't have to

00:24:38.819 --> 00:24:41.540
redo it every time you create a different design matrix.

00:24:41.540 --> 00:24:43.619
You can just sort of recycle those computations.

00:24:44.060 --> 00:24:48.859
And so that saves you a lot of time potentially when you're creating these things.

00:24:49.260 --> 00:24:53.060
Or if you're doing something complicated like you like an auto encoder or some some

00:24:53.060 --> 00:24:58.660
really like complex and big part of these recipes, you can you can basically cache the

00:24:59.099 --> 00:25:01.420
results up to that point, which is kind of a nice feature.

00:25:04.060 --> 00:25:06.780
So, you know, this is kind of like the shock and awe slide.

00:25:07.540 --> 00:25:10.979
Here are the things that I've gotten into recipes so far.

00:25:11.619 --> 00:25:16.180
You have a lot of basic things like loots and roots and logs and polynomials and all

00:25:16.180 --> 00:25:21.859
that stuff. Again, anything I'm missing here, whether it's obscure or not, please let

00:25:21.900 --> 00:25:25.900
me know. There are a bunch of things we can do with encodings now, so we can do, of

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:28.900
course, dummy variables, which is sort of a standard thing.

00:25:29.180 --> 00:25:32.619
You know, one thing you could do, like in the Sacramento data set, is there's a

00:25:32.619 --> 00:25:33.660
predictor for city.

00:25:33.939 --> 00:25:39.339
So you might want to include the actual city as a as a different dummy variable in the

00:25:39.339 --> 00:25:43.380
model. But the problem is, you know, even though we have a thousand or so data points,

00:25:43.380 --> 00:25:46.619
some of these cities only have two or three instances in the data.

00:25:46.979 --> 00:25:51.459
So what you'd like to be able to do is to dynamically say, well, you know, give me

00:25:51.660 --> 00:25:57.939
dummy variables. But, you know, if the frequency of any group in that in that factor

00:25:57.939 --> 00:26:02.500
is very small, let's say like 1 percent or 5 percent or whatever your tolerance is, can

00:26:02.500 --> 00:26:05.660
you change the factor levels and dump those into an other level?

00:26:06.339 --> 00:26:08.579
You can do that for cats and in vitriol.

00:26:08.619 --> 00:26:10.459
I think you can do that in those packages.

00:26:11.020 --> 00:26:14.819
But, you know, you can have a step that would actually sort of reassemble the factor

00:26:14.819 --> 00:26:15.939
levels based on that.

00:26:17.099 --> 00:26:20.339
I'm not a big fan of binning, but, you know, we have discretization steps.

00:26:21.099 --> 00:26:25.420
One other cool thing I had for an example or a data set I've been working on is let's say

00:26:25.420 --> 00:26:27.380
you have a predictor that is a date field.

00:26:27.420 --> 00:26:31.900
You know, it's a date class and are, you know, you're probably not going to analyze it

00:26:31.900 --> 00:26:35.979
as a date. You want to analyze whether the month has an effect or the day of the week

00:26:35.979 --> 00:26:40.939
has an effect. And so we have a step that basically can do all the encodings for dates

00:26:40.939 --> 00:26:44.619
if you want to take that single column of your data and make a bunch of features out of

00:26:44.619 --> 00:26:47.780
that for different ways to represent dates where you can do that.

00:26:48.300 --> 00:26:50.819
It also give you indicators if you want it for holidays.

00:26:51.140 --> 00:26:54.900
So, you know, if you're modeling something that is dependent on whether that date is a

00:26:54.900 --> 00:26:58.020
holiday or not, you might want to have pretty much in your model for that.

00:26:58.060 --> 00:27:00.619
So we have a nice holiday, holiday step.

00:27:01.939 --> 00:27:05.579
Similar to care, we have a bunch of filters for, you know, highly correlated predictors and

00:27:05.579 --> 00:27:10.420
things like that. Imputation right now, keen ears, neighbors, back trees, simple mean

00:27:10.420 --> 00:27:11.540
mode, imputation.

00:27:12.819 --> 00:27:14.579
You know, there's a lot more you can put in there.

00:27:14.579 --> 00:27:17.140
Simple normalization, transformation type things.

00:27:17.380 --> 00:27:19.140
Again, these are very similar to what's in carrot.

00:27:19.540 --> 00:27:24.260
And again, if there's anything missing here, please let me know.

00:27:25.260 --> 00:27:30.900
There's a great package called Dimred, D-I-M-R-E-D, and I kind of capitalized on that

00:27:30.900 --> 00:27:35.380
where it has a nice interface to a bunch of dimension reduction operations.

00:27:35.780 --> 00:27:39.739
And so, you know, right now it's really easy for you to do a step that's PCA or kernel

00:27:39.739 --> 00:27:42.219
PCA. So you might have a bunch of variables.

00:27:42.219 --> 00:27:43.459
This is an example I'll show in a minute.

00:27:43.780 --> 00:27:47.300
You might have a ton of variables that you just want to do some plotting with and you

00:27:47.300 --> 00:27:50.260
might need to log some things and maybe do some transformations.

00:27:50.500 --> 00:27:53.699
And so what I'll show you in a minute is you can try a bunch of different dimension

00:27:53.699 --> 00:27:57.500
reduction techniques without redoing a bunch of computations prior to that.

00:27:57.819 --> 00:28:00.900
So there's there's a lot of steps here that will allow you to do these things.

00:28:01.300 --> 00:28:04.500
And there's things like, you know, basic expansions and interactions, which, of

00:28:04.500 --> 00:28:07.500
course, we need. And there's a lot more to put in.

00:28:07.500 --> 00:28:11.219
You know, I've got a little list in GitHub, you know, a bunch of things that you can

00:28:11.219 --> 00:28:15.020
look up, you know, trying to find a good autoencoder package.

00:28:15.300 --> 00:28:20.619
There's more imputation methods that we can be done here, like a singular value

00:28:20.619 --> 00:28:22.660
decomposition. So there's a lot there.

00:28:22.939 --> 00:28:24.380
There's a lot of documentation qualities.

00:28:24.380 --> 00:28:27.500
But again, you know, let me know if there's something really lacking here.

00:28:29.819 --> 00:28:33.500
So, you know, I've already mentioned you might have said, well, Max, you know, the

00:28:33.500 --> 00:28:35.579
recipe you had before started off with a formula.

00:28:35.579 --> 00:28:39.619
I thought we were trying to get away from formula method and that would be right.

00:28:39.619 --> 00:28:44.540
The value of using the formula in the initial recipe is if you only have an outcome

00:28:44.540 --> 00:28:50.180
in or outcomes and predictors, you know, that's the most syntactically concise way

00:28:50.180 --> 00:28:54.020
of doing it, because the situation is not that complicated in terms of roles.

00:28:54.300 --> 00:28:56.380
Let's say you do have something more complicated.

00:28:56.619 --> 00:28:59.660
Another way of assembling the recipe is not using formula.

00:29:00.099 --> 00:29:04.739
So you can say, you know, I want to have a recipe and the data is the original data

00:29:04.739 --> 00:29:06.339
set is here.

00:29:07.099 --> 00:29:10.699
And then what you can do is you can take all the variables that are in that data set

00:29:10.699 --> 00:29:14.979
and they'll be available and then you can start defining their roles so you can add a

00:29:14.979 --> 00:29:16.859
role for price being the outcome.

00:29:17.180 --> 00:29:18.300
And these are not hard coded.

00:29:18.300 --> 00:29:21.219
There's not like a pre-specified list that you have to choose from.

00:29:21.579 --> 00:29:26.500
So if you want to come up with some new type of role for whatever modeling method

00:29:26.500 --> 00:29:28.380
you're doing, this is basically like pretext.

00:29:28.380 --> 00:29:29.660
You can put in whatever you want.

00:29:29.939 --> 00:29:33.300
Now, we do use outcome and predictor a lot in the package.

00:29:33.300 --> 00:29:37.260
So if that's the traditional roles these things are playing, stick to outcome and stick

00:29:37.260 --> 00:29:40.619
to predictor. But let's say you want to have the zip code as a stratification variable.

00:29:40.619 --> 00:29:44.579
So you might want to fit this linear model separately for every zip code.

00:29:45.619 --> 00:29:51.020
And so you can have that column in your data set come along for the ride, not be created

00:29:51.020 --> 00:29:52.180
into dummy variables.

00:29:52.380 --> 00:29:57.339
And then when you extract that using the bake function, you know what its role is and

00:29:57.339 --> 00:29:58.339
you know what you can get.

00:29:58.819 --> 00:30:04.540
So so as an example, if you wanted to have a little wrapper around linear regression,

00:30:05.099 --> 00:30:09.739
you know, the underlying function that does the linear model fit is called LM dot fit

00:30:09.739 --> 00:30:12.180
and takes an X variable, which is your design matrix.

00:30:12.180 --> 00:30:14.900
And it takes a Y variable that is your vector.

00:30:15.300 --> 00:30:17.900
I think it has to be a vector of numbers.

00:30:18.300 --> 00:30:23.979
You could have that function be parameterized in terms of a recipe and some data.

00:30:24.380 --> 00:30:29.380
And then inside that function, you could actually do the prepare bit because the recipe

00:30:29.380 --> 00:30:33.219
already has the steps all pre-specified, so you don't need to specify them here.

00:30:34.099 --> 00:30:40.260
And then when you fit LM, you can just get the design matrix by doing bake and then add

00:30:40.260 --> 00:30:45.219
dplyr selectors for what variables you want to be returned from that call.

00:30:45.219 --> 00:30:49.819
So if I just want the predictors, my design matrix would basically be this.

00:30:50.140 --> 00:30:54.140
And then if I only want the outcome, I can do the same thing, you know, use this bake

00:30:54.140 --> 00:30:55.859
command, but only get the outcome back.

00:30:56.459 --> 00:31:02.300
And so, you know, again, if you had stratification variables, you could say, you know, role is

00:31:02.619 --> 00:31:05.660
strata or whatever you want to select these things by roles.

00:31:07.020 --> 00:31:12.540
One other nice thing about this is since the steps are all sort of independent of each

00:31:12.540 --> 00:31:15.300
other, you know, this isn't baked in quite yet.

00:31:15.540 --> 00:31:20.060
Sorry, I should use another food analogy, but this isn't really written yet.

00:31:20.060 --> 00:31:24.500
But the cool thing is, is if we have some preprocessing method that's available, let's

00:31:24.500 --> 00:31:28.739
say in scikit-learn and we have scikit-learn installed on a computer, you know, it

00:31:28.739 --> 00:31:34.780
wouldn't be hard to write a step that would then connect R to Python, pass the data to

00:31:34.780 --> 00:31:41.219
Python, have it do the preprocessing there, return all the information it needs to do

00:31:41.219 --> 00:31:45.339
that technique on new data and have that come along.

00:31:45.339 --> 00:31:48.819
So, you know, R is sort of our default compute engine here.

00:31:49.180 --> 00:31:53.900
But we can certainly, since these things are sort of like modularized, we can

00:31:53.900 --> 00:31:57.699
certainly do that with, you know, Weka or TensorFlow or what have you.

00:31:57.699 --> 00:32:02.020
As long as that stuff is installed when you're in a place where you're using R and

00:32:02.020 --> 00:32:07.859
you have code to make that connection, we can start writing steps for other packages

00:32:07.859 --> 00:32:09.459
basically. So that's kind of a cool thing.

00:32:10.180 --> 00:32:13.020
Not available yet, but it's there, it will be there eventually.

00:32:13.660 --> 00:32:18.300
So here's an example in our book, we took some data, some image segmentation data

00:32:18.300 --> 00:32:24.939
where people took a bunch of images of cells and sometimes the imaging software did a

00:32:24.939 --> 00:32:28.459
good job of saying where the cell boundary is and other times it didn't.

00:32:28.900 --> 00:32:31.180
So that's called segmentation of a cell.

00:32:31.380 --> 00:32:36.780
And so we have a data set where we have a couple thousand rows, we have a couple

00:32:36.780 --> 00:32:42.180
thousand images and cells, and they've been already classified as being well

00:32:42.180 --> 00:32:43.939
segmented or poorly segmented.

00:32:44.459 --> 00:32:48.859
And they wanted to have a model that basically predicted that based on a bunch of

00:32:48.859 --> 00:32:54.099
imaging derived qualities of those cells, like how big they are, how they're shaped

00:32:54.219 --> 00:33:00.579
and so on. And so basically we want to build a model that takes the imaging data and

00:33:00.579 --> 00:33:04.500
then makes a prediction on whether that cell was well segmented or poorly segmented.

00:33:04.500 --> 00:33:07.619
Because if we really think strongly it was poorly segmented, we probably want to

00:33:07.619 --> 00:33:10.459
filter those cells out of our subsequent analysis.

00:33:10.900 --> 00:33:14.660
So we can build a model to do that.

00:33:15.180 --> 00:33:16.780
I'm not really going to do the model building here.

00:33:16.780 --> 00:33:22.420
What I want to do is show there's 58 imaging predictors in this data set and many of

00:33:22.420 --> 00:33:23.739
them are highly, highly correlated.

00:33:24.140 --> 00:33:27.300
So if we want to look at our data and say, OK, are there any outliers here?

00:33:27.619 --> 00:33:30.180
Are there any weird features in the data?

00:33:30.219 --> 00:33:35.500
We might do some dimensional reduction techniques to figure out how can we project

00:33:35.500 --> 00:33:39.900
those 58 dimensions down to only a few dimensions and still capture what's going on

00:33:39.900 --> 00:33:43.859
in that data set. So I'll use some steps based on dimensional reduction to highlight

00:33:43.859 --> 00:33:48.060
that. So let's say you were to add or if you hadn't loaded dplyr or caret, you would

00:33:48.060 --> 00:33:56.380
load those. The data is in the segmentation data object and then segmentation data

00:33:56.380 --> 00:34:01.540
has the original authors pre-specified what data they use for training, what data

00:34:01.540 --> 00:34:02.579
they use for testing.

00:34:02.939 --> 00:34:07.900
So I'm going to use a little piping here and filter out to make this training version

00:34:07.900 --> 00:34:14.340
of the data set. I'll filter out or I'll keep only the ones that had ksql train and

00:34:14.340 --> 00:34:21.379
then I'll get rid of two columns in that data set that are the data set identifier

00:34:21.379 --> 00:34:24.739
and the actual number of the cell, like it's individual cell ID.

00:34:25.139 --> 00:34:26.179
And then I do the same thing.

00:34:26.179 --> 00:34:30.739
So I have a data set that only has the original idea of a test that was there's about a

00:34:30.739 --> 00:34:32.699
thousand cells in each one of these data sets.

00:34:33.020 --> 00:34:38.699
So what I'll do is I'll estimate any statistics I need from the training sets, like the

00:34:38.699 --> 00:34:42.540
PCA loadings and things like that, and then apply them to the test set.

00:34:42.939 --> 00:34:44.860
And then that's what I'll do the graphics on.

00:34:45.780 --> 00:34:47.340
So that's the data set we'll use.

00:34:47.860 --> 00:34:49.820
So we'll start off with just a simple recipe.

00:34:50.659 --> 00:34:54.659
The class variable is the one that is a factor that is whether something is well

00:34:54.659 --> 00:34:55.939
segmented or poorly segmented.

00:34:56.419 --> 00:35:02.219
And I'll say, you know, everything else in the data set besides that class variable is a

00:35:02.219 --> 00:35:06.500
potential predictor. So that's the basic recipe where I've declared the rules for

00:35:06.500 --> 00:35:10.459
everything. And then what I'm going to do is some of these predictors are extremely

00:35:10.459 --> 00:35:16.860
skewed. And so that can mess up some of the things like PCA that use variance as an

00:35:16.860 --> 00:35:19.340
objective function and how they do their computations.

00:35:20.179 --> 00:35:22.620
Now, some of these predictors are negative and highly skewed.

00:35:22.860 --> 00:35:25.899
And so there's this thing called the Al Johnson transform, which is sort of like the

00:35:25.899 --> 00:35:27.300
Box-Cox transformation.

00:35:27.540 --> 00:35:30.219
And it can have the effect of un-skewing your data.

00:35:30.699 --> 00:35:34.979
And we use this one instead of Box-Cox because Box-Cox requires your data to be

00:35:35.939 --> 00:35:39.340
non-negative. It can't be well, it can be zero, has to be strictly positive.

00:35:40.100 --> 00:35:41.540
And some of our data is not like that.

00:35:41.979 --> 00:35:46.620
So we're saying is all the predictors in our data set, we're going to estimate and apply

00:35:46.620 --> 00:35:50.219
this Al Johnson transformation to make them a little less skewed.

00:35:50.699 --> 00:35:53.780
And then some of these dimensional reduction techniques, we're going to want to

00:35:53.780 --> 00:35:55.419
center and scale our predictors.

00:35:55.979 --> 00:35:58.100
So, again, we've only said what we want to do here.

00:35:58.139 --> 00:35:59.260
We haven't done anything yet.

00:36:00.260 --> 00:36:02.979
There's three basic steps so far that we've sort of declared.

00:36:03.500 --> 00:36:06.659
And then when I prepare that recipe, I've just kept the same name.

00:36:07.060 --> 00:36:09.620
We're going to estimate these things from the training set.

00:36:10.699 --> 00:36:13.699
I'm going to tell it not to print out the steps just because.

00:36:14.020 --> 00:36:17.939
And then I'm going to use this retain equal true again, and that'll allow us to recycle all

00:36:17.939 --> 00:36:22.419
these computations to get created in subsequent steps.

00:36:25.459 --> 00:36:27.219
So let's say I want to do principal component analysis.

00:36:27.260 --> 00:36:33.820
Well, what I can do is I can take this sort of pre-trained recipe and add a step for

00:36:33.820 --> 00:36:34.860
principal component analysis.

00:36:35.659 --> 00:36:39.100
And so what this says is, hey, do PCA on all the predictors in the data set.

00:36:39.100 --> 00:36:41.459
Now, they're all numeric, so I don't need to specify their type.

00:36:42.459 --> 00:36:47.340
And this other option says is, you know, give me the number of PCA components that will

00:36:47.340 --> 00:36:50.620
capture 90 percent, basically the variability in the predictors.

00:36:50.659 --> 00:36:55.979
And so, you know, I don't know right now how many predictors that is, but it will give me

00:36:55.979 --> 00:36:59.979
enough to capture that information to make sure I have a pretty good representation of my

00:36:59.979 --> 00:37:04.979
original data. So, again, what I've done here is I've just added a added a

00:37:04.979 --> 00:37:08.699
specification as to what I want, but I haven't actually done PCA yet.

00:37:09.179 --> 00:37:11.459
So there's a summary function for recipes.

00:37:11.459 --> 00:37:15.419
And when you run a summary function on it, what it tells you is what the available

00:37:15.419 --> 00:37:21.100
variables are, what they're, you know, at this point in the recipe, what their type is,

00:37:21.100 --> 00:37:23.780
are they numbers or are they factors and things like that.

00:37:23.979 --> 00:37:28.219
It tells you their role and whether there are variables that have been derived or the

00:37:28.219 --> 00:37:31.739
original variables. And so you can see right now I have 59 variables.

00:37:31.739 --> 00:37:34.459
So there's 48 predictors in an outcome class.

00:37:34.979 --> 00:37:38.139
And and that's what it is, because I haven't done PCA yet.

00:37:38.139 --> 00:37:41.860
I haven't transformed this into principal components because I haven't prepared it yet.

00:37:42.500 --> 00:37:44.820
And so then let's say we do that preparation.

00:37:45.739 --> 00:37:48.739
We don't have to re-estimate again centering and scaling these things.

00:37:49.060 --> 00:37:53.260
But this four step when we do the pair function on it computes all the loadings that we

00:37:53.260 --> 00:37:54.379
need to do PCA.

00:37:54.699 --> 00:37:59.580
And then if I do the summary method on that, now it's telling me the things that are

00:37:59.580 --> 00:38:04.659
available in the recipe or these variables called PCA1, PCA2, because I've actually done

00:38:04.659 --> 00:38:09.419
the recipe. So, you know, what variables are available to you at any given time can

00:38:09.419 --> 00:38:12.300
change depending on what you're asking it to do at each step.

00:38:12.820 --> 00:38:17.379
So prior to PCA, even though I said are in scale and transform these variables, they

00:38:17.379 --> 00:38:18.979
were there under the original name.

00:38:19.340 --> 00:38:22.820
But now that I've done PCA, they're there under a different name.

00:38:24.300 --> 00:38:29.260
So now we have the components, we can we can bake them and get their actual values for

00:38:29.260 --> 00:38:34.620
the test set. And then if you just do a simple GG plot, you can see, you know,

00:38:34.620 --> 00:38:37.500
at least using PCA, what kind of separation do I have in the data?

00:38:37.899 --> 00:38:40.100
I don't really see any outliers here per se.

00:38:40.340 --> 00:38:42.739
And there's, you know, a fair amount of overlap in the data.

00:38:43.139 --> 00:38:47.419
So, you know, how difficult of a modeling problem this is doesn't mean it's

00:38:47.419 --> 00:38:51.659
impossible, but at least from a linear classifier standpoint, you can get an idea that

00:38:51.659 --> 00:38:54.260
there's some separation, but not complete separation.

00:38:55.300 --> 00:38:58.179
But you might think, well, you know, there might be some other sort of feature

00:38:58.179 --> 00:38:59.780
engineering type things I can do.

00:39:00.179 --> 00:39:04.379
And one of the things is if you've ever heard of support vector machines, what you can

00:39:04.379 --> 00:39:08.699
do is you can, let's say, project your original predictors into another higher

00:39:08.699 --> 00:39:11.739
dimensional space that that might be a nonlinear transformation.

00:39:12.179 --> 00:39:16.419
So you can sort of apply these sort of nonlinear transformations of your data in this

00:39:16.419 --> 00:39:18.260
thing called kernel principle component analysis.

00:39:18.260 --> 00:39:23.459
We'll do that transformation and then do PCA on top of the expanded dimensionality of

00:39:23.459 --> 00:39:27.419
your predictors. And the Kernelab package has a way to do that.

00:39:27.419 --> 00:39:28.620
We have a step for doing that.

00:39:29.100 --> 00:39:35.139
So, you know, our PCA recipe utilized that basic recipe that just did the centering and

00:39:35.139 --> 00:39:36.379
scaling and transformation.

00:39:36.739 --> 00:39:41.620
And so instead of doing the regular PCA, now we can start with that original recipe and

00:39:41.620 --> 00:39:45.100
create another one that does our kernel principle component analysis.

00:39:45.340 --> 00:39:49.020
We have to tell what kernel to use and some of the parameters, which I've done here.

00:39:49.860 --> 00:39:53.580
But when we prepare that, we're only, you know, this has nothing to do with the PCA

00:39:53.580 --> 00:39:57.780
analysis we did previously, but it re-estimates everything it needs to for the kernel

00:39:57.780 --> 00:40:00.979
PCA. We bake that to get the values for the test set.

00:40:00.979 --> 00:40:03.179
And again, we can just ggplot that away.

00:40:03.459 --> 00:40:09.179
Here you see a little different distributions, but I think there's a little bit more

00:40:09.179 --> 00:40:14.300
separation between the classes by doing this kernel transformation beforehand.

00:40:14.699 --> 00:40:17.459
So, you know, this might be a good sort of feature engineering step to do.

00:40:18.260 --> 00:40:20.820
You know, you can do like an isomap transformation, things like that.

00:40:20.820 --> 00:40:23.500
There are many other dimension reduction techniques you can do.

00:40:24.419 --> 00:40:30.459
A really simple one you can also try is since we know the classes, we can compute sort of

00:40:30.459 --> 00:40:33.219
the multidimensional class centroids for each class.

00:40:33.219 --> 00:40:35.459
So we can take a 58 dimensional space.

00:40:35.459 --> 00:40:40.020
We can find the center of the distribution for the well segmented predictors in the center

00:40:40.020 --> 00:40:42.699
of the distribution for the poorly segmented cells.

00:40:43.820 --> 00:40:47.780
And then this step class this will will compute that.

00:40:47.780 --> 00:40:51.739
And then when you want to get new predictors, it will actually compute the distance of

00:40:51.739 --> 00:40:55.580
every individual data point to the centroid of the original classes.

00:40:55.979 --> 00:41:00.620
So it's almost like doing like a linear discriminant analysis and in here.

00:41:01.260 --> 00:41:05.699
But it's sort of a as a pre-processing step rather than as a model.

00:41:06.179 --> 00:41:08.020
And so you can add a step for that.

00:41:08.020 --> 00:41:12.459
Again, use all the predictors since you need to know the classes to do the centroids.

00:41:12.459 --> 00:41:13.979
You need to tell what class to use.

00:41:13.979 --> 00:41:15.300
And that's this variable here.

00:41:15.580 --> 00:41:17.540
And these are distances which need to be skewed.

00:41:17.540 --> 00:41:23.659
So let's just log transform those predictors that we get that come out of this class this step.

00:41:24.340 --> 00:41:26.540
And so, again, we prepare that.

00:41:27.139 --> 00:41:29.780
We don't have to redo computations and then we bake them.

00:41:30.620 --> 00:41:33.540
The data that comes out of that is we have the original class.

00:41:34.219 --> 00:41:35.459
You can see how the matches here.

00:41:35.459 --> 00:41:40.899
It says, give me all the variables in the computed recipe that start with class, whether

00:41:40.899 --> 00:41:42.820
it's uppercase C or lowercase C.

00:41:43.620 --> 00:41:45.139
And I have the original class variable.

00:41:45.459 --> 00:41:51.659
And then the distances to the to the poorly segmented class centroid in the well segmented

00:41:51.659 --> 00:41:56.100
class centroid. And it turns out when you do that, I think you get the most separation

00:41:56.100 --> 00:41:57.899
between these these data.

00:41:57.899 --> 00:41:59.939
You do see some outliers that are induced here.

00:42:00.860 --> 00:42:02.459
You might want to look into those data points.

00:42:02.860 --> 00:42:07.820
But if you know what we did here is we did some different feature engineering steps

00:42:08.659 --> 00:42:12.340
utilizing this basic recipe and just kind of layered them on without having to redo a

00:42:12.340 --> 00:42:13.340
bunch of computations.

00:42:13.899 --> 00:42:18.699
So, you know, you can do the same thing with models where you might then put these design

00:42:18.699 --> 00:42:24.659
matrices into various models to see what does better or worse for the for the model that

00:42:24.659 --> 00:42:29.139
you're trying to use. And hopefully this is illustrated where you can just recycle all

00:42:29.139 --> 00:42:32.139
these computations and the sort of simplicity of doing that.

00:42:33.739 --> 00:42:38.139
So that's the example just to give you an idea of the next steps.

