00:46:37.540 --> 00:46:43.979
The thing is, any steps that you do, they have to be operations that you would apply to

00:46:43.979 --> 00:46:49.820
any data set. And so if you think about splitting data, you're going to differentially do

00:46:49.820 --> 00:46:52.179
things to each data set.

00:46:52.580 --> 00:46:54.419
So I'm trying to think of a better way to say that.

00:46:54.580 --> 00:46:58.540
So one thing I thought about including is there's a bunch of sub sampling methodologies

00:46:58.540 --> 00:47:00.580
like if you have class amounts, it's like downsampling.

00:47:00.580 --> 00:47:02.100
And I thought, oh, that would make a great step.

00:47:02.100 --> 00:47:03.100
I should put that in here.

00:47:03.340 --> 00:47:05.459
But you don't necessarily want to always downsample.

00:47:05.459 --> 00:47:07.820
So you might want to downsample your training set.

00:47:07.860 --> 00:47:10.979
But when you go to make predictions on your test set, you don't want to downsample that.

00:47:11.379 --> 00:47:16.340
So I've kind of left splitting steps out of there and things that would filter rows.

00:47:16.340 --> 00:47:17.699
For the most part, I've done that.

00:47:18.100 --> 00:47:23.939
Now, one thing that we're talking about doing is and this is just we're just talking about

00:47:23.939 --> 00:47:28.340
this right now. I haven't implemented anything is being able to include deep layer type

00:47:28.340 --> 00:47:29.899
filters in steps.

00:47:30.219 --> 00:47:33.179
So you might, you know, pipe in a step to do centering and scaling.

00:47:33.179 --> 00:47:36.979
But then you want to, let's say, filter on some variable that's there.

00:47:37.300 --> 00:47:42.820
So you can imagine doing a filter by or filter, which is in deep layer to a recipe.

00:47:43.179 --> 00:47:47.860
And there are some some of those deep layer operations that I don't see any reason why

00:47:47.860 --> 00:47:49.300
they wouldn't work here.

00:47:49.540 --> 00:47:51.820
So there might be ways of doing that in the future.

00:47:51.820 --> 00:47:57.419
But I haven't coded them up, but just realize anything you do in a step is something that

00:47:57.419 --> 00:48:00.899
you're going to always do to whatever data you're applying it to.

00:48:01.860 --> 00:48:07.260
So there might be some some things that you don't want to include in the step in terms of

