00:51:28.860 --> 00:51:32.219
Why does extend carrot rather than create a new recipe package?

00:51:32.219 --> 00:51:33.219
That's a great question.

00:51:34.139 --> 00:51:35.699
I mean, you know, I love carrot.

00:51:35.699 --> 00:51:36.820
I love working on that.

00:51:36.820 --> 00:51:38.100
And I'm still working on that.

00:51:39.340 --> 00:51:44.860
The thing about carrot is it's very, very monolithic in the sense that if you've ever used it,

00:51:44.860 --> 00:51:52.060
you know, the way resampling or preprocessing and things like that, it's all embedded into sort of one big function.

00:51:52.379 --> 00:51:57.020
And so when you want to make modifications to the system, that, you know, the concept of

00:51:57.500 --> 00:52:03.459
that, you know, the consequences of doing that, since it's not very modular, are pretty severe, to be honest with you.

00:52:03.699 --> 00:52:09.820
And so the idea of having a separate package is it sort of isolates those new things that you want to do without you

00:52:10.260 --> 00:52:12.739
worrying about backward compatibility.

00:52:12.739 --> 00:52:15.659
You don't have to worry about, well, wait, how does this affect this and that?

00:52:15.899 --> 00:52:22.899
So it's easier to make a separate package that has these steps and these sort of ideas in it and make adapters for carrot

00:52:23.219 --> 00:52:25.620
than funneling all this stuff into carrot.

00:52:26.419 --> 00:52:31.300
Another good reason not to do this in carrot is carrot already has like a lot of dependencies.

00:52:31.580 --> 00:52:38.179
And so I don't want to like double down on that just for the sake of how long it takes Crayon to check these things.

00:52:39.060 --> 00:52:45.820
So it's more, you know, the idea going forward is to have more modular blocks of code in different packages.

00:52:47.219 --> 00:52:50.300
You know, like like a good example might be like like GG plot, right?

00:52:50.300 --> 00:52:55.260
I mean, we could always take everything that people want to do with GG plots and just add them in the original package.

00:52:55.260 --> 00:52:58.899
But it's actually easier just to have extensions of GG plot in different packages.

00:52:58.899 --> 00:52:59.979
Same thing with Shiny, right?

00:52:59.979 --> 00:53:04.179
I mean, it's better not to have everything in one huge package.

00:53:05.020 --> 00:53:05.780
Probably in time.

